# Getting the lenght of each message, in number of words:
data['len_words'] = data['raw'].map(lambda s: len(s.split(' ')))

# We can see the distribution of the lenght differs in each class:

f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax1.hist(data[data['class']==0]['len_words'], normed = True, bins = 25, range=[0, 40])
ax1.set_title('Ham: Number of Words')
ax2.hist(data[data['class']==1]['len_words'], normed = True, bins = 25, color = 'r')
ax2.set_title('Spam: Number of Words')
f.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.15)
In [6]:
# We could think the ammount of upper case chars relative to the number of chars in each message is indicative of spam/ham:
data['len_chars'] = data['raw'].map(lambda s: len(s))

data['n_upper'] = data['raw'].map(lambda s: len(re.findall('([A-Z])',string=s)))
data['n_upper_ratio'] = data['n_upper']/data['len_chars']

# The distribution also differs a bit:
f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax1.hist(data[data['class']==0]['n_upper_ratio'], normed = True, bins = 50, range =[0,0.5])
ax1.set_title('Ham: Uppercase chars / chars')
ax2.hist(data[data['class']==1]['n_upper_ratio'], normed = True, bins = 50, color = 'r', range =[0,0.5])
ax2.set_title('Spam: Uppercase chars / chars')
f.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.15)

# Next up we'll get the number of numerical charachters in each text:
data['n_numerical'] = data['raw'].map(lambda s: len(re.findall('([0-9])',string=s)))
data['n_numerical_ratio'] = data['n_numerical']/data['len_chars']

# The distribution also differs a bit:
f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax1.hist(data[data['class']==0]['n_numerical_ratio'], normed = True, bins = 25, range =[0,0.5])
ax1.set_title('Ham: Numerical chars / chars')
ax2.hist(data[data['class']==1]['n_numerical_ratio'], normed = True, bins = 25, color = 'r', range =[0,0.5])
ax2.set_title('Spam: Numerical chars/ chars')
f.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.15)

# Wordcloud visualization:

def get_class_words(data,stop_set = None):
    spam_raw = data[data['class'] == 1]['raw']
    spam_text = ''
    for item in spam_raw:
        if stop_set is not None:
            if item in stop_dict:
                continue
        spam_text += item

    ham_raw = data[data['class'] == 0]['raw']
    ham_text = ''
    for item in ham_raw:
        if stop_set is not None:
            if item in stop_dict:
                continue        
        ham_text += item

    return(spam_text,ham_text)

spam_text, ham_text = get_class_words(data)
spam_wordcloud = WordCloud().generate(spam_text)    

ham_wordcloud = WordCloud().generate(ham_text)

# As it looks like Naive Bayes is the best approach even after all the feature engineering...
# let's try a even naiver approach:

stopwords_set = set(stopwords.words('english'))

train_spam, train_ham = get_class_words(train)

train_spam_list = train_spam.lower().split()
train_ham_list = train_ham.lower().split()

def clean_list(wordlist,stop_set):
    def_list = []
    for word in wordlist:
        if word not in stop_set:
            def_list.append(word)
    return(def_list)

train_spam_clean = clean_list(train_spam_list,stopwords_set)
train_ham_clean = clean_list(train_ham_list,stopwords_set)

spam_most_common = Counter(train_spam_clean).most_common(30)
ham_most_common = Counter(train_ham_clean).most_common(30)
joint_vocab = set()
for element in ham_most_common:
    joint_vocab.add(element[0])

for element in spam_most_common:
    joint_vocab.add(element[0])
In [215]:
# Now we vectorize the SMS with this vocabulary:
def check_word(text,word):
    if word.lower() in text.lower():
        return(1)
    return(0)

for element in joint_vocab:
    train[element] = train['raw'].apply(check_word,args = (element,))
    test[element] = test['raw'].apply(check_word,args = (element,))
